messages.content: My identity is something I think about very often, especially because I had trouble in the past understanding how difficult it was to put a label on something as personal and undefinable as identity. I grew up both in suburban New York and Tokyo, and was exposed to some different races and ethnicities in New York, but with middle- to upper-class Italian Americans making up a large portion of the school population, Latinx being the next largest group, and then a fair number of African Americans and Asians. I grew up speaking Japanese at home, learned French in preschool, English once I moved to New York at age seven, where I also learned Spanish and Italian in the foreign language program at school, then took German in high school and Spanish in college. Three words to describe my identity would be flexible, persistent, and understanding. One thing I noticed when we did the identity wheel exercise in class was that I tended to not identify myself as any social characteristic; they are certainly crucial parts to my identity, but they have never been and still are not the identities that come to mind immediately. This ties in with my first trait of being flexible, which I believe was fostered through moving many times and being judged in the context of the new environment every time, and also having have to adapt to these new environments. I do not identify as Japanese because I find myself in certain situations where everyone else is also Japanese and it is not a defining character of mine, not that identity has to be distinct, but it is better for the sake of your self-worth. I do not know where my persistence came from, but my parents claim it was from when I was very young, and I would make my parents read me a book over and over until I memorized it. It also showed in my language learning; I was extremely determined to find a way to communicate with my peers and did everything I could do improve as quickly as possible. As a result, with the help of my supportive teachers, I graduated from the ESL class in five months. I would say I am understanding because I have been in different positions in different social contexts so many times, so I can empathize with other people a lot easily. That is something that has changed over the years; I have always been sociable, friendly, and empathetic, but that has been enforced by my moving experiences. I think people in my life see me in a similar way as I perceive myself, but I also understand that these characteristic traits are double-edged. Just regarding those three words, I know some perceive me as not having a strong will, stubborn, or caring too much about othersâ opinions. I understand and accept those perspectives because I do not use irrefutable characteristics â Japanese, Asian, female, etc. â as my identity. I purposely do so because as the famous philosopher Kierkegaard said, âOnce you label me, you negate me,â labeling puts so much more than just the label onto you; you inevitably get attached to any generalizations that sometimes you do not relate with. For me, I would rather be seen as stubborn than to be just a representative of a social group, no matter how proud I was of that group.
